    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="508"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d508">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.1731/68</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 140</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-29">September 29,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The receipt is acknowledged of your despatch No.
                    464 of September 11, 1934,<note n="34" xml:id="d508fn34">Not printed.</note>
                    quoting the translated text of a Nicaraguan press item stating that information
                    had been obtained from the Department of State to the effect that there was
                    under contemplation a barter plan whereby Nicaragua, Honduras and Guatemala
                    would pay in coffee for a percentage of their imports.</p>
                <p>In this regard, you are informed that in the exploratory studies of trade
                    agreements which are now being made no consideration is being given to any plan
                    for the barter or exchange of commodities. In your conversations with officials
                    of the Foreign Office you may make such use of this information as may appear
                    advisable.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sumner Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
